{
  "title": "Deploying Batch Jobs Using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to deploy batch jobs using the FastAPI framework with Python 3.12+, focusing on asynchronous processing and handling long-running tasks efficiently.",

  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI is a modern, fast (high-performance), web framework for building APIs with Python 3.7+.",
    "Python 3.12+ enhances the flexibility of FastAPI by providing better support for asynchronous processing and handling long-running tasks.",
    "In this guide, we will learn how to create a simple API that accepts batch jobs and processes them using the `asyncio` library in Python 3.12+.",
    "We'll explore how FastAPI's built-in support for dependency injection simplifies creating asynchronous functions and handling multiple concurrent requests efficiently.",
    "By the end of this guide, you will have a working example of a batch job processing API that you can easily adapt to your own projects."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": "from fastapi import FastAPI\napp = FastAPI()\n\nasync def process_job(job: Job):\n    # Process the job here...\n\n@app.post('/jobs/')\nasynchronous def create_job():\n    job = await Job.create()\n    return {'job_id': job.id}"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ is required for the advanced asynchronous features used in this example.",
    "FastAPI version 0.76.0 or higher is recommended."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "Although Python 3.12+ provides improved support for asynchronous processing, it's essential to be mindful of potential performance bottlenecks caused by I/O-bound tasks.",
    "Ensure you have a suitable asyncio loop policy (e.g., `uvloop`) installed and configured for optimal performance."
  ]
}
